commit.message: add (i)mul tests

rework (i)mul instructions to set flags correctly

Processor manuals say Z, S, P, A flags are 'undefined'. But experiments on
some CPUs show they are set based on the result resp. lower half of the
result.
add (i)div opcode tests
fix typo

rework (i)div and (i)mul instructions

In detail:
  - correct overflow detection for (i)mul
  - correct overflow detection (raise #DE exception) for (i)div
  - always use the __HAS_LONG_LONG__ code versions
  - don't change flags with (i)div; manual says 'flags are undefined', experiments
    on real cpus show this means 'unchanged'

commit.message: add '--32' option to demo program to start in 32-bit mode

ops2: Add packed SSE ops

Add SSE ops:
* movhlps
* movlps
* movhps
* unpcklps
* unpckhps

Signed-off-by: Patrick Rudolph <patrick.rudolph@9elements.com>

ops2: Add SSE instructions

Add support for:
* movups
* movaps
* movntps
* andps
* andnps
* orps
* xorps

Manually tested and verified that register content is valid.

Signed-off-by: Patrick Rudolph <patrick.rudolph@9elements.com>

decode: Prepare for SSE support

For i686 emulation we need to add SSE emulation.
Add basic infrastructure for SSE ops.

Signed-off-by: Patrick Rudolph <patrick.rudolph@9elements.com>

ops2: Introduce a callback function for MSR access

As MSRs are machine specific, introduce a callback function that allows
the user to handle this instructions.

It allows to either redirect them to the host or emulate different pc
platforms outside of this library.

Signed-off-by: Patrick Rudolph <patrick.rudolph@9elements.com>

ops2: Add cpuid support using a new handler

As CPUID instruction is very complex and depends on the CPU emulated,
allow to install a handler which does all the magic.

Allows to redirect the instruction to the host or emulate different pc
platforms outside of this library.

Signed-off-by: Patrick Rudolph <patrick.rudolph@9elements.com>

prim_ops: Fix compiler warning

Fix additional warnings found by -Wimplicit-fallthrough

Signed-off-by: Patrick Rudolph <patrick.rudolph@9elements.com>
